  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════ SOLUTIONS.YAML ══ -->
  <section id="solutions" class="docs-section">
    <h2 class="docs-section-title">
      solutions.yaml — Complete Reference
      <span class="docs-section-badge" style="background:color-mix(in srgb,#2DD4BF 12%,transparent);color:#2DD4BF;border:1px solid color-mix(in srgb,#2DD4BF 30%,transparent)">Public companion</span>
    </h2>
    <p><code>solutions.yaml</code> is the companion file to <code>course.yaml</code>. It contains all answers, grading rubrics, and sample solutions — one entry per question. The automation engine joins them at runtime using <code>question_id</code>.</p>
    <div class="docs-callout docs-callout--tip">
      <span class="docs-callout__icon">✓</span>
      <div class="docs-callout__body"><strong>Commit solutions.yaml with the course.</strong> The grader reads it from the same course directory. Learners are expected to submit their own work with integrity.</div>
    </div>

    <h3 style="font-size:0.95rem;font-weight:700;color:var(--text-primary);margin:1.5rem 0 0.5rem">Metadata</h3>
    <div class="docs-pre">
      <div class="docs-pre__bar"><span class="docs-pre__dot"></span><span class="docs-pre__dot"></span><span class="docs-pre__dot"></span><span class="docs-pre__lang">yaml</span></div>
      <code>metadata:
  course_id: git-mastery          # must match course.yaml metadata.id exactly
  course_version: "1.0.0"         # must match course.yaml metadata.version
  schema_version: "3.0"           # do not change
  updated_at: "2025-01-15"        # update whenever any answer changes
  maintainer: janesmith           # GitHub username
  visibility: public              # public for transparent grading</code>
    </div>

    <h3 style="font-size:0.95rem;font-weight:700;color:var(--text-primary);margin:1.5rem 0 0.5rem">Answer format by question type</h3>
    <div class="docs-table-wrap">
      <table class="docs-table">
        <thead><tr><th>Type</th><th>Answer field(s)</th><th>Format</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td><code>mcq</code></td><td><code>answer</code></td><td>0-indexed integer: <code>1</code> means option B</td></tr>
          <tr><td><code>multi</code></td><td><code>answers</code></td><td>List of 0-indexed integers: <code>[0, 2]</code> means A and C</td></tr>
          <tr><td><code>truefalse</code></td><td><code>answer</code></td><td>Boolean: <code>true</code> or <code>false</code></td></tr>
          <tr><td><code>short</code></td><td><code>sample_answer</code> + <code>keywords[]</code></td><td>Free text + required keyword list for scoring</td></tr>
          <tr><td><code>code_output</code></td><td><code>answer</code></td><td>0-indexed integer (index into options[])</td></tr>
          <tr><td><code>code_fix</code></td><td><code>correct_code</code></td><td>Full corrected code block as a literal YAML string</td></tr>
          <tr><td><code>code_write</code></td><td><code>sample_solution</code></td><td>One correct implementation + optional alternatives</td></tr>
          <tr><td><code>code_reading</code></td><td><code>answer</code></td><td>0-indexed integer (index into options[])</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <h3 style="font-size:0.95rem;font-weight:700;color:var(--text-primary);margin:1.5rem 0 0.5rem">Solution entries</h3>
    <div class="docs-pre">
      <div class="docs-pre__bar"><span class="docs-pre__dot"></span><span class="docs-pre__dot"></span><span class="docs-pre__dot"></span><span class="docs-pre__lang">yaml</span></div>
      <code>solutions:

  # ── mcq ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  - question_id: ctest-ch-01-s-01-q-01     # exact copy from course.yaml
    type: mcq
    points: 2
    difficulty: easy
    answer: 1                               # 0-indexed: option B = "tree"
    explanation: |
      A tree object in Git stores a directory listing — it records the name,
      mode, and SHA-1 of each blob or subtree it contains.

  # ── truefalse ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  - question_id: ctest-ch-01-s-01-q-02
    type: truefalse
    points: 1
    difficulty: easy
    answer: false
    explanation: |
      The working tree contains your actual files on disk. The staging area
      (index) is a snapshot of what will go into the next commit.

  # ── short ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  - question_id: final-s-01-q-01
    type: short
    points: 5
    difficulty: medium
    sample_answer: |
      Merge creates a merge commit preserving both branch histories.
      Rebase rewrites commits onto the target branch creating a linear history.
      Prefer merge for shared/public branches; prefer rebase for local cleanup
      before merging a feature branch.
    keywords:
      - "merge commit"
      - "linear"
      - "rebase"
      - "shared"
      - "history"
    grading_rubric:
      - criterion: "Correctly defines merge commit"
        points: 1
      - criterion: "Correctly defines rebase"
        points: 1
      - criterion: "Identifies when to use each"
        points: 2
      - criterion: "Mentions shared branch concern"
        points: 1
    explanation: |
      Rebase on a shared branch rewrites history others have based work on,
      causing divergent histories. Use merge for shared branches.

  # ── code_write ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  - question_id: ctest-ch-02-s-01-q-03
    type: code_write
    points: 5
    difficulty: medium
    sample_solution: |
      def two_sum(nums, target):
          seen = &#123;&#125;
          for i, n in enumerate(nums):
              if target - n in seen:
                  return [seen[target - n], i]
              seen[n] = i
    alternative_solutions:
      - |
        def two_sum(nums, target):
            for i in range(len(nums)):
                for j in range(i + 1, len(nums)):
                    if nums[i] + nums[j] == target:
                        return [i, j]
    grading_rubric:
      - criterion: "Returns correct indices"
        points: 2
      - criterion: "Handles duplicate values"
        points: 1
      - criterion: "Runs in better than O(n²) time"
        points: 2
    explanation: |
      The hash-map approach runs in O(n) time and O(n) space.
      The brute force nested loop is O(n²) and receives partial credit.

  # ── code_fix ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  - question_id: ctest-ch-03-s-02-q-01
    type: code_fix
    points: 3
    difficulty: medium
    correct_code: |
      def factorial(n):
          if n == 0:
              return 1
          return n * factorial(n - 1)
    bugs_fixed:
      - "Missing base case — original returned None for n=0"
      - "Off-by-one: original compared n == 1 not n == 0"
    grading_rubric:
      - criterion: "Correct base case n == 0"
        points: 2
      - criterion: "Recursive call is correct"
        points: 1
    explanation: |
      The factorial of 0 is 1 by mathematical definition.
      Without this base case the recursion infinitely recurses.

# ── Assignment review guides (optional) ─────────────────────────────────────
assignment_review_guides:
  - assignment_id: cassign-ch-01
    what_to_look_for:
      - "At least 5 commits with descriptive, imperative subject lines"
      - "Feature branches used and merged"
      - "README explains what the project does"
    common_mistakes:
      - "Commits named 'fix' or 'update' with no context"
      - "All work done directly on main"
    edge_cases:
      - "Private repos: ask student to add reviewer as collaborator"
    feedback_notes: "Encourage conventional commit style for next assignment"
    feedback_template: |
      Hi @&#123;github_username&#125;,

      Thanks for your submission. Here's feedback on your repository:

      **Strengths:**
      &#123;strengths&#125;

      **Areas to improve:**
      &#123;improvements&#125;

      Your score: &#123;score&#125;/20 (&#123;percentage&#125;%)
      Status: &#123;pass_fail&#125;</code>
    </div>
  </section>


  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════ QUESTION TYPES ═══════ -->
  <section id="questions" class="docs-section">
    <h2 class="docs-section-title">Question Types — Full Reference</h2>
    <p>All 8 question types work in chapter tests, the final test, and ungraded in-lesson quizzes. In chapter tests and final tests, answers must be in <code>solutions.yaml</code>.</p>
    <div class="docs-table-wrap">
      <table class="docs-table">
        <thead><tr><th>Type</th><th>Course.yaml fields</th><th>Grading</th><th>Partial credit</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td><code>mcq</code></td>
            <td><code>question</code>, <code>options[]</code>, <code>points</code></td>
            <td>Exact match on 0-indexed answer</td>
            <td>No</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><code>multi</code></td>
            <td><code>question</code>, <code>options[]</code>, <code>points</code></td>
            <td>Score = correct_selected / total_correct × points</td>
            <td>Yes</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><code>truefalse</code></td>
            <td><code>question</code>, <code>points</code></td>
            <td>Exact match on boolean</td>
            <td>No</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><code>short</code></td>
            <td><code>question</code>, <code>keywords[]</code>, <code>points</code></td>
            <td>Keyword matching: matched_keywords / total_keywords × points</td>
            <td>Yes</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><code>code_output</code></td>
            <td><code>question</code>, <code>code</code>, <code>options[]</code>, <code>points</code></td>
            <td>Exact match on 0-indexed option</td>
            <td>No</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><code>code_fix</code></td>
            <td><code>question</code>, <code>code</code>, <code>grading</code>, <code>points</code></td>
            <td>Structural diff against correct_code; or Docker sandbox execution</td>
            <td>Via rubric</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><code>code_write</code></td>
            <td><code>question</code>, <code>starter</code>, <code>grading</code>, <code>points</code></td>
            <td>Docker sandbox: passed_tests / total_tests × points</td>
            <td>Yes</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><code>code_reading</code></td>
            <td><code>question</code>, <code>code</code>, <code>options[]</code>, <code>points</code></td>
            <td>Exact match on 0-indexed option</td>
            <td>No</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <div class="docs-callout docs-callout--info">
      <span class="docs-callout__icon">ℹ️</span>
      <div class="docs-callout__body">All grading is deterministic. There is no AI, no semantic matching. Code questions run in a Docker sandbox: <code>--network none --memory 256m --cpus 1 --read-only --user 1001:1001 --security-opt no-new-privileges</code>.</div>
    </div>
  </section>


  <!-- ════════════════════════════════════════════════════ PR WORKFLOW ══════ -->
  <section id="pr-workflow" class="docs-section">
    <h2 class="docs-section-title">PR Workflow — Publish a Course</h2>
    <div class="docs-steps" style="--ch-color:#a78bfa">
      <div class="docs-step">
        <div class="docs-step__line"><div class="docs-step__num">1</div><div class="docs-step__connector"></div></div>
        <div class="docs-step__body">
          <p class="docs-step__title">Copy the template and write your course</p>
          <p class="docs-step__desc">
            <code>cp -r engine/courses/template engine/courses/your-slug</code><br>
            Fill in <code>course.yaml</code> (all REQUIRED fields), complete <code>content_blueprint</code>, and add <code>solutions.yaml</code> with answers, rubrics, and sample solutions. Set <code>metadata.status: review</code> when ready.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="docs-step">
        <div class="docs-step__line"><div class="docs-step__num">2</div><div class="docs-step__connector"></div></div>
        <div class="docs-step__body">
          <p class="docs-step__title">Open a Pull Request</p>
          <p class="docs-step__desc">PR title: <code>[Course] your-slug — Course Title</code>. The PR should contain the full course directory, including <code>course.yaml</code>, <code>solutions.yaml</code>, and referenced assets.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="docs-step">
        <div class="docs-step__line"><div class="docs-step__num">3</div><div class="docs-step__connector"></div></div>
        <div class="docs-step__body">
          <p class="docs-step__title"><code>validate-pr.yml</code> runs automatically</p>
          <p class="docs-step__desc">Validates the YAML schema, checks all required fields, verifies asset file references, and reports warnings as a PR comment. Fix any errors before requesting review.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="docs-step">
        <div class="docs-step__line"><div class="docs-step__num">4</div><div class="docs-step__connector"></div></div>
        <div class="docs-step__body">
          <p class="docs-step__title">Maintainer reviews and merges</p>
          <p class="docs-step__desc">The lead maintainer reviews content quality, fact-checks credits, and merges the PR. Set <code>metadata.status: published</code> before merge.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="docs-step">
        <div class="docs-step__line"><div class="docs-step__num">5</div><div class="docs-step__connector"></div></div>
        <div class="docs-step__body">
          <p class="docs-step__title"><code>course-publish.yml</code> fires on merge</p>
          <p class="docs-step__desc">Runs <code>parse-course.ts</code> → writes <code>course.json</code> and <code>course-detail.json</code>. Then <code>sync-site-data.yml</code> aggregates all course data. Then <code>deploy-site.yml</code> rebuilds the site. Live in ~90 seconds.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>


  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════ CHECKLIST ════ -->
  <section id="checklist" class="docs-section">
    <h2 class="docs-section-title">Pre-PR Checklist</h2>
    <p>Check every item before opening your PR. The validator catches most issues — this checklist catches the rest.</p>
    <ul class="docs-checklist">
      <li><code>metadata.id</code> is kebab-case, globally unique, matches your directory name</li>
      <li><code>metadata.status</code> is set to <code>review</code> or <code>published</code> (not <code>draft</code>)</li>
      <li><code>schema_version</code> is <code>"3.0"</code> — not changed</li>
      <li><code>content_blueprint</code> explains the open-source-first content flow, resources, tests, capstone, and contribution path</li>
      <li>Every chapter has a matching <code>chapter_test_id</code> in <code>chapter_tests[]</code></li>
      <li>Every <code>chapter_tests[]</code> section has at least one question</li>
      <li>Every question <code>id</code> is globally unique within the course</li>
      <li>Every <code>credit_id</code> referenced in a lesson has a matching entry in <code>credits[]</code></li>
      <li><code>classification.category</code> is one of the 12 valid track slugs</li>
      <li>All lesson/resource asset files listed in <code>assets[]</code> actually exist in the directory</li>
      <li>No course-level banner, thumbnail, OG, or certificate badge files are required; the site generates abstracts from the selected category</li>
      <li><code>changelog</code> has at least one entry with a version, date, and changes</li>
      <li><code>solutions.yaml</code> is included in the PR and reviewed for accuracy</li>
      <li>Every question in <code>chapter_tests[]</code> and <code>final_test</code> has a matching entry in <code>solutions.yaml</code></li>
      <li><code>certificate.enabled</code> is set and requirements are correct</li>
      <li>All video URLs are reachable (run <code>check-links.yml</code> locally if in doubt)</li>
      <li>PR only touches files under <code>engine/courses/your-slug/</code></li>
    </ul>
  </section>
